[Cases of bovine tuberculosis in domestic animals other than cattle have shown an increase in the UK in recent years. These involved cats, pigs, South American camelids (llamas and alpacas), and deer, and -- less frequently -- other species, including dogs, goats, sheep, feral mink, ferrets, rats, and mice. _Mycobacterium bovis_ was first diagnosed in camelids in Great Britain in 1999; several human infections attributed to an alpaca source have been registered since.

UK's recent statistics of bovine tuberculosis in cattle are available at https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/310857/bovinetb-dataset-14may14.xls.

Final results of the tests in Norway and of the epidemiological investigations in the UK and in Norway (possible contacts since their arrival), are anticipated.

For further reading, with special reference to diagnosis in South American camelids, please refer to the following review:
Schiller I, Oesch B, Vordermeier HM, et al: Bovine tuberculosis: a review of current and emerging diagnostic techniques in view of their relevance for disease control and eradication. Transbound Emerg Dis. 2010 Aug 1; 57(4): 205-20. doi: 10.1111/j.1865-1682.2010.01148.x; available at http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1865-1682.2010.01148.x/full. - Mod.AS

